Let $S$ be a set of $2 times 2$ matrices with complex numbers as entries, and
let $T$ be the subset of $S$ consisting of matrices whose eigenvalues are
$plus.minus 1$ (so the eigenvalues for each matrix in $T$ are ${ 1, 1 }$ or ${
1, -1 }$ or ${ -1, -1 }$). Suppose there are exactly three matrices in $T$.
Prove that there are matrices $A, B$ in $S$ such that $A B$ is not a matrix in
$S$. (Note: $A = B$ is allowed).
